It's World Refugee Day, and we're reflecting on the reality that more than 100 MILLION children, women, and men are displaced globally. These are individuals who faced persecution, conflict, violence, or human rights violations and were forced to flee their homes. In 2022, we're seeing the highest population of forcibly displaced people ever recorded, including 26.6 million refugees. This isn't just a statistic. There are faces, stories, and shattered dreams behind the numbers. Let's do our part to welcome them with open arms. #refugees #WorldRefugeeDay

Gold's Fit Tip of the week: Here's a low-calorie, high protein option for any meal or even meal prep! Directions: 1. Place steaks on grid over medium, ash-covered coals. Grill steaks, covered, 11 to 14 minutes (over medium heat on a preheated gas grill, covered, 11 to 15 minutes) for medium-rare (145°F) to medium (160°F) doneness, turning occasionally. A table-top griddle or frying pan can be used if you don’t have a grill. 2. Meanwhile, to prepare the dressing, whisk together soy sauce and sesame oil in a small bowl; set aside. 3. Divide rice evenly among four bowls. Top rice with vegetables and kimchi. 4. Carve steaks into thin pieces and divide evenly among bowls. Drizzle with dressing. Garnish with green onions and optional sesame seeds. #goldsgymsocal #goldsgym #bestgymintheworld #iconic #resultsforeverybody #recipe #protein #dotfit #fit #lean #clean

Today is the 62nd anniversary of the first Nashville sit-in to protest racial segregation at lunch counters in the South. It should be a day to celebrate victory over segregation, but what do I see when I get on a local news site but an article about a local school board hosting separate meetings for white people and black people. The Issaquah School Board says they're doing this to protect black folks who don't feel comfortable around white folks, but it's funny, because that's the exact same reasoning used to justify "separate but equal" facilities in the Jim Crow South. Back in those days, it was the white folks who supposedly didn't feel comfortable drinking at the same fountains, using the same bathrooms, and eating at the same lunch counters with colored folks. But other than that, everything's the same. At least in Issaquah. Segregation has been outlawed all over the country, but apparently the Issaquah School Board hasn't gotten the message yet. There are a couple ways to deal with segregation. One is lawsuits and one is civil disobedience. In other words, sit-ins, like they did in Nashville. Of the two methods, I like sit-ins better. Any time a public official tells you you can't go to a meeting because you're the wrong color, you should go to that meeting anyway. And when you do, bring some of your friends along. Then report back to us on what happens. –David

It’s the Weekend, take a moment to focus on deep breathing. . . . . . Remember to breathe. When we take slow and deep breaths it can calm down both our body and our mind. Square breathing is one of the most popular breathing techniques to help us focus on our breath, slow it down, and/or practice a moment of mindfulness. You breathe in for a count of 4, hold for 4, breathe out for 4, and hold for 4 counts. . . . #breathe #mentalhealth #mentalillness #mentalhealthawareness #anxiety #mentalhealthmatters #minoritymentalhealth #ptsd #depression #nobodyshaming #psychology #stress #recovery #blackmentalhealth #mentalhealthrecovery #selfcare #suicide #prevention #blackboyjoy #blackpeople #bewell

NORTHEAST NEWSREEL HISTORIC REDWOOD GROVE BEING RETURNED California Redwood Forest Returned to Native American Tribes By BRIAN MELLEY LOS ANGELES (AP) — The descendants of Native American tribes on the Northern California coast are reclaiming a bit of their heritage that includes ancient redwoods that have stood since their ancestors walked the land. Save the Redwoods League planned to announce Tuesday that it is transferring more than 500 acres (202 hectares) on the Lost Coast to the InterTribal Sinkyone Wilderness Council. The group of 10 tribes that have inhabited the area for thousands of years will be responsible for protecting the land dubbed Tc’ih-Léh-Dûñ, or “Fish Run Place,” in the Sinkyone language. Priscilla Hunter, chairwoman of the Sinkyone Council, said it’s fitting they will be caretakers of the land where her people were removed or forced to flee before the forest was largely stripped for timber. “It’s a real blessing,” said Hunter, of the Coyote Valley Band of Pomo Indians. “It’s like a healing for our ancestors. I know our ancestors are happy. This was given to us to protect.” The transfer marks a step in the growing Land Back movement to return Indigenous homelands to the descendants of those who lived there for millennia before European settlers arrived. The league first worked with the Sinkyone council when it transferred a 164-acre (66-hectare) plot nearby to the group in 2012. The league recently paid $37 million for a scenic 5-mile (8-kilometer) stretch of the rugged and forbidding Lost Coast from a lumber company to protect it from logging and eventually open it up to the public. Opening access to the public is not a priority on the property being transferred to the tribal group because it is so remote, said Sam Hodder, president and CEO of the league. But it serves an important puzzle piece wedged between other protected areas. Steep hills rise and fall to a tributary of the Eel River that has steelhead trout and Coho salmon. The property was last logged about 30 years ago and still has a large number of old-growth redwoods, as well as second-growth trees. “This is a property where you can almost tangibly feel that it is healing, that it is recovering,” Hodder said. “You walk through the forest and, even as you see the kind of ghostly stumps of ancient trees that were harvested, you could also in the foggy landscape see the monsters that were left behind as well as the young redwoods that are sprouting from those stumps.” The league purchased the land two years ago for $3.5 million funded by Pacific Gas & Electric Co. to provide habitat for endangered northern spotted owl and marbled murrelet to mitigate other environmental damage by the utility. PG&E was set to emerge Tuesday from five years of criminal probation for a 2010 explosion triggered by its natural gas lines that blew up a San Bruno neighborhood and killed eight people. It's been blamed since 2017 for sparking more than 30 wildfires that wiped out more than 23,000 homes and businesses and killed more than 100 people. In an effort to reduce its liability and the chance of vegetation contacting power lines and sparking fires, PG&E has been criticized for destroying many large and old trees. “Thanks to Save the Redwoods League for seizing on any opportunity to protect lands on the Lost Coast that are vital to its conservation,” said Michael Evenson, vice president of the Lost Coast League, which advocates for protecting water and wildlife in the area. “But PG&E getting a green merit badge after all the destruction they’re doing ... is not palatable.” Hawk Rosales, former executive director of the council, said the new property adds a significant holding to the 4,000 acres (1,618.7 hectares) the group protects for cultural and ecological purposes. More importantly, it recognizes the tribal group’s importance in caring for lands. “For so many decades tribal voices have been marginalized in the mainstream conservation movement,” Rosales said. “It’s only until very recently that they have been invited to participate meaningfully and to take a leadership role.” Hodder said the league was trying to remove barriers and increase the scale of land managed by tribal communities and return Indigenous knowledge and practices, such as setting small controlled fires to clear out undergrowth that lead to healthier forests. “These communities have been stewarding these lands across thousands of years," Hodder said. “It was the exclusion of that stewardship in many ways that’s gotten us into the mess that we’re in.”

Pamela Moses, was sentenced to six years and one day on Monday following an attempt to register to vote in 2019. Moses had a certificate from her probation office saying that she was no longer on probation at the time of attempting to register to vote, but later received an email by another correction official in the probation office stating the officer made an “error.” This error is representative of the many cases with people who live in Tennessee with felonies. Korean Ginseng Authentic (Panax ginseng C A Meyer / Araliaceae) standardized to 5% [17.5 mg] ginsenosides per capsule AlchePharma utilizes authentic, Korean ginseng (Panax ginseng C A Meyer / Araliaceae). The number of ginsenoside types contained in Korean ginseng (38 ginsenosides) is substantially more than that of ginsenoside types contained in American ginseng (19 ginsenosides). Furthermore, Korean ginseng has been identified to contain more main non-saponin compounds, phenol compounds, acid polysaccharides and polyethylene compounds than American ginseng and Sanchi ginseng. Korean ginseng (Panax ginseng C A Meyer / Araliaceae ) is one of the most heavily studied ginsengs in the world and is traditionally used as an important herbal medicine in Far East Asia. Our Korean Ginseng is standardized to 5% [17.5 mg] ginsenosides per 350 mg capsule of Panax ginseng root extract powder. * The German botanist Nees Von Esenbeck first classified Korean ginseng as Panax shinseng var. coraiensis Nees in 1833, with the term coraiensis referring to Korea as its wild habitat. The Russian botanist Carl Anton Meyer renamed the plant Panax ginseng in 1843. For many years, Korea has operated the Office of Monopoly, to safeguard and oversee the quality of ginseng that is produced in Korea. All ginseng products that are sold must bear the seal of the Office of Monopoly. It is illegal to remove ginseng seeds from Korea in an attempt to cultivate them elsewhere. Ginseng. CHSA is proud to announce the San Francisco Board of Supervisors' resolution offering a formal apology to Chinese immigrants and their descendants over past atrocities. In a landmark unanimous vote, the resolution introduced by Supervisor Matt Haney in partnership with former SFUD students was approved last week by the board’s Budget and Finance Committee. The resolution cited numerous instances of racism against the Chinese community dating back to the 19th century, including SFUSD’s closure of Chinese schools between 1870-1885. It also apologizes for the three-day riot in 1877 that targeted the Chinese community: four people died and dozens of Chinese-owned laundries were destroyed or looted. In addition, the resolution acknowledges current ongoing racism and violence against the Chinese and AAPI communities amid the COVID-19 pandemic and pledges budget investments in support of the AAPI community. CHSA will be hosting a press conference along with Supervisor Haney, members of the API Council, and former students on Wednesday, February 2 at 9am with the formal apology. The announcement and ceremony will take place outside the CHSA museum on Joice Street. 📷: https://www.instagram.com/photobykev_/ ~~~~~ Chinese Historical Society of America Gordon Mar 馬兆明 Connie Chan 陳詩敏 London Breed 倫敦．布里德

This #AlumniWednesday, we're celebrating two Temple FMA alums who are going to have their short films featured in the final streaming block of the Philadelphia Latino Film Festival. Monica Moore-Suriyage ('14), featured in Jordan Peele's documentary Horror Noire as part of the next generation of Black horror filmmakers, offers La Ciguapa Siempre, which follows a young woman, Milagro, as she goes on a camping trip with her boyfriend after learning she was adopted, and discovers the truth to her identity deep in the woods. Less terrifying but just as haunted, María Teresa Rodríguez (MFA '97) tells a comic and semi-surreal tale with Cuban American Gothic, about a woman living alone during the early 2020 pandemic whose Cuban parents return from the dead to remind her of their immigrant journey and give her the strength to meet the moment. Both of these films are available as part of PHLAFF's Bloque Tres, which starts streaming on June 3 and runs through June 5. Umoja Karamu, meaning “unity feast” in Swahili, is an African-American celebration begun in 1971 by Dr. Edward Sims, Jr. Celebrated in a manner similar to Thanksgiving, Umoja Karamu is held on the fourth Sunday in November. Its purpose is to instill solidarity, black values, and appreciation of black heritage into black families. https://newafrikan77.wordpress.com/2016/11/21/umoja-karamu-unity-feast-thanks-to-afrikan-culture-tradition-history/

Repost from @aclu_nationwide • Andraya Yearwood has used her voice to speak out on behalf of student athletes like herself, participating in national interviews and documentaries during her high school career. While Andraya already graduated, there’s a group in her home state attempting to take away all records of her past athletic achievements. We joined a lawsuit to defend Andraya in court against those attacks last November. This pattern of discrimination and exclusion toward trans students is one we’ve seen nationwide: state legislatures have proposed, and even passed, all-out bans on our participation in sports. These laws are about nothing more than erasing and excluding us from all aspects of public life. But we’re sending a message to state politicians that if you come for one of us, you have to get through ALL of us. Let’s thank Andraya for her leadership this #WomensHistoryMonth

Once again the Government is long on self-congratulation but late on delivery with its announcement of an Australian travel bubble, but Jacinda Ardern couldn’t treat us like lucky little prisoners any longer. In an extraordinary admission today COVID-19 Response Minister Chris Hipkins said each country would be making decisions unilaterally. In other words, there is no bubble, New Zealand will just start behaving like an Australian state, only six months late. Today’s announcement incidentally aligns with the policies ACT has been espousing for months – all of them in our COVID Response Plan 2.0. For the Prime Minister to get up today and talk about ‘green zones’ at airports like she discovered something new and deserved a Nobel Prize for it is galling in the extreme. Holding up a traffic light system on a sheet of A3 paper like the one epidemiologist Professors Michael Baker and Nick Wilson mooted months ago is also outrageous. It’s been obvious that all these steps were the way forward since New South Wales introduced them in October. We know quarantine-free travel will work and it will improve the lives of countless New Zealanders and Australians. It’s how the Australian states have been working for months and there is no excuse for New Zealand being so late to join.

It has recently come to our attention that some people may have ethical concerns about Breaking the Chain's decision to host an event that serves alcoholic beverages. With that said we would like to make the following statement. "Breaking the Chains understands that everyone does not hold the same views and moral considerations. However, it is very important to us that we are inclusive of all entities and individuals who want to support and/or be apart of Breaking the Chains. Our main annual event will continue to be the Promise Banquet, which as you know is a more family friendly and of course an alcohol free event. I pray that the heart of the church is big enough to understand that the mission of Breaking the Chains to provide hope, healing, and restoration to survivors of human trafficking is and will always be rooted in the love of Jesus Christ, and not the individual convictions of denominations and/or people ." We deeply value everyone who gives of their time, talents, and resources. TOGETHER we are Breaking the Chains!

Strong to severe storms continue to look likely for SW portions of Iowa late tonight, especially the southwestern quarter of the state. Portions of Nebraska have been upgraded to a 'moderate' risk for severe weather, while parts of Iowa have been increased to an 'Enhanced' risk. Storms will move into the SW portion of the state after 10-11pm and continue to trek eastward into the overnight. Storms will weaken as they move eastward, but the threats for damaging winds will exist for areas to the southwest, as well as a risk for large hail and to a lesser extent an isolated tornado.

Shalom! I’m Adam Godes, a Real Estate Agent with Gold Group Realty from Minneapolis, Minnesota. Here's a little about me—including what I’d be if I were a Jewish dish, and my favorite holiday, which is coming up! Get in touch at https://www.thegold.group:=:https://www.thegold.group/ Q: What synagogue do you go to? A: Beth El Q: What is your favorite Jewish holiday and tradition? A: Passover—if it weren’t for the people that sacrificed before us, we wouldn’t be where we are today and that deserves to be celebrated. Doesn’t hurt that it falls at a time which signals warmer weather is on the way! Q: If you were a Jewish dish, what dish would you be and why? A: Hamantashen—sometimes I can be a little hard on the outside, but once we get past that, I promise there’s a sweet part on the inside that will always be there! Q: Why do you like being Jewish A: Many of my closest relationships have resulted from my religion. I know that I will always be surrounded by a great group of people and appreciate all of the relationships and connections that have come from my Jewish roots over the years. #sponsored #partner

Let's talk banned books! Books often explore complex topics such as social issues, history, and personal experience. In many cases, those that contain materials that may be troubling for some audiences or may conflict with some audience members' values get challenged or banned. However, censoring a book in this way takes away opportunities to learn about experiences that are similar to or different from our own. As a public library, we are vigilant on issues of censorship so that these voices can be available for future generations to hear from. Set in 1941, The Bluest Eye tells the story of a young African-American girl named Pecola as she deals with external and internalized racism. Pecola has always been referred to as ugly because of her Blackness, which leads to her wanting blue eyes so that she can achieve this mythical beauty seemingly reserved only for white people. You can find this book in our physical and digital collections! [Image description: A colorful graphic shows the cover of the book, which is blank with the title written in blue text. Text at the top of the graphic reads "Banned and challenged books: The Bluest Eye." Under that, a list reads Black girlhood, racism and equality, counter narrative, internalized racism, and Great Depression." At the bottom is a section surrounded by police caution tape. The section reads "Child sexual abuse, sexually explicit, contains controversial issues, violence, language, and unsuited for age group."] #LovelandPublicLibrary #LovelandColorado #BannedBooks #Censorship #WhatLibrariesDo #TheBluestEye #ReadBannedBooks #ToniMorrison #BookBanning

Join us tomorrow on Thursday, March 24th 12PM to 1PM for our weekly Lunch & Learn series! We welcome Dr. Kazumi Hatasa as our guest speaker for this exciting event. Kazumi Hatasa received his Ph.D. in Education from University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign in 1989. He started teaching at Purdue University in 1988. He is currently a professor in School of Languages and Cultures. He was Director of the School of Japanese at Middlebury College from 2004 to 2018. He co-authored the Japanese language textbook series Nakama (Cengage Learning). He has also been working with professional rakugo performers to introduce students to this traditional performing art. His most recent publication is Meshiagare (Kurosio Publisher), an advanced level textbook in Japanese focusing on Japanese culinary culture. This Black Maternal Health Week, we want to deepen the conversation about Black maternal health in the U.S. Providing safe, compassionate care is key to improving Black maternal health. There is more work to do, but here’s what we’re doing to tackle the disparities starting with our team members: • Reevaluating VCU’s School of Medicine curriculum, residency, and faculty training with a DEI focus. • Mandatory implicit bias and DEI training. • Department DEI Taskforces.
